07901nam a22010335i 9780824874520DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029833969  a(OCoLC)1032693031  a(OCoLC)1037980460  a(OCoLC)1042028438  a(OCoLC)1046605259  a(OCoLC)1047000578  a(OCoLC)1049627166  a(OCoLC)1054872295  a97808248745207 a10.1515/97808248745202doi  a(DE-B1597)484328  a(OCoLC)1024008610  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aE184.A75bL52 2006 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a307.089/9501752122200aFrom Urban Enclave to Ethnic Suburb :bNew Asian Communities in Pacific Rim Countries /ced. by Wei Li. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Asian Immigration and Community in the Pacific Rim -- tMaking America at Eden Center -- tFlushing 2000: Geographic Explorations in Asian New York -- tSpatial Transformation of an Urban Ethnic Community: From Chinatown to Ethnoburb in Los Angeles -- tKoreans in Greater Los Angeles: Socioeconomic Polarization, Ethnic Attachment, and Residential Patterns -- tAsian Americans in Silicon Valley: High-Technology Industry Development and Community Transformation -- tSuburban Housing and Indoor Shopping: The Production of the Contemporary Chinese Landscape in Toronto -- tHong Kong Business, Money, and Migration in Vancouver, Canada -- tThe Social Construction of an Indochinese Australian Neighborhood in Sydney: The Case of Cabramatta -- tThe Chinese in Auckland: Changing Profiles in a More Diverse Society -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Urban Enclave to Ethnic Suburb focuses on the migration, settlement, and adaptation of Chinese and other Asian immigrants and their impacts on the transformation of metropolitan areas in the United States, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand. These stories of the interactivity of Asian "people and place" in four nation-states are framed within the larger context of spatial and social patterns, migration, acculturation/assimilation, and racialization theories, and emerging landscapes in the inner cities and suburbs of metropolitan areas like Los Angeles, San Francisco, New York, Toronto, Vancouver, Sydney, and Auckland. The book's primary arguments center on revisioning traditional "assimilationist" models of the Chicago School with the context of today's evolving metropolis. Other key elements include immigrant and refugee policies, new theories of ethnic settlement, and urban and suburban immigrant landscape forms. Nine chapters document the experiences of Asian immigrants and refugees--rich and poor, old and new. Their communities vary from no identifiable residential cluster (Vietnamese in Northern Virginia) to multiple residential and business clusters in both inner city and suburbs (Koreans in Los Angeles, Chinese in Toronto) to the largest suburban Chinese residential and business concentration (the San Gabriel Valley of suburban Los Angeles) and the "high-tech Mecca" of the U.S., if not the world (Silicon Valley), whose growth has been inseparable from workers, professionals, and entrepreneurs of Asian descents who are often local residents as well.Rich in detail and broad in scope, From Urban Enclave to Ethnic Suburb is the first book to focus exclusively on the Asian immigrant communities in multiethnic suburbs. It effectively demonstrates the complexity of contemporary Asian immigrant and refugee groups and the strength of their communities across the Pacific Rim. It will be welcomed by a wide range of readers with interests in Asian American studies, urban geography, the Chinese diaspora, immigration, and transnationalism. Contributors: Richard Bedford, Kevin Dunn, David W. Edgington, Michael A. Goldberg, Elsie Ho, Thomas A. Hutton, Hans Dieter Laux, Wei Li, Lucia Lo, John R. Logan, Edward J. W. Park, Suzannah Roberts, Christopher J. Smith, Günter Thieme, Joseph S. Wood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAsianszAustralia. 0aAsianszCanada. 0aAsianszNew Zealand. 0aAsianszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBedford, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunn, Kevin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdgington, David W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHo, Elsie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutton, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaux, Hans Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Wei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Wei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLo, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogan, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Edward J. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Suzannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Christopher J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThieme, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWood, Joseph S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Pa